          "answerType"       :"freeText",
          "required"         :false,
          "answerPlaceholder":"Your thoughts...",
          "sampleAnswer"     :"Temptation rarely presents itself as obviously wrong — it works by appealing to genuine desires and legitimate needs, and then offering a forbidden route to satisfying them. The fruit wasn't ugly or obviously poisonous; it looked good and seemed to offer real benefits. Temptation typically works this way: it takes something we legitimately want — comfort, significance, pleasure, security — and points us toward getting it in a way that bypasses or contradicts what God has said. The appeal is real, which is precisely what makes the choice difficult.",
          "questionHint"     :"If the fruit was genuinely attractive and seemed to offer real benefits, what does that tell you about why temptation is so hard to resist?",
