          "elementId"    :"ch03-el14",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "text"         :"The problem here is not just Eve and Adam <em>breaking</em> the rules (although they do do that). The problem is that <em>they</em> want to become the ones who <em>make</em> the rules. In reaching out to take the fruit, they are reaching out to take God's place. They want to be the rule-makers in their own lives. And very often we are just like them.",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch03-el15",
          "type"         :"heading",
          "subtype"      :"section",
          "level"        :"2",
          "format"       :"plainText",
          "text"         :"Everything changes",
          "bottomPadding":"normal"
        },

        {
          "elementId"    :"ch03-el16",
          "type"         :"text",
          "subtype"      :"bridge",
          "format"       :"HTML",
          "text"         :"The moment they eat, something shifts. They expected to gain; instead, they feel exposed. The eyes that were opened don't see wisdom — they see their own nakedness, and they are ashamed.<br><br>Then they hear God approaching, and they hide. This is new. Nothing in Genesis 2 suggested any reason to hide from God. Now, instinctively, that is exactly what they do.",
