  "howToUseData":{
    "sections":[
      {
        "heading":"Who Is This Study For?",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"People asking the big questions",
            "body" :"Genesis opens with the questions most people ask at some point: Where did everything come from? Does my life have any meaning? Is there a God — and if so, what is He like? If you are genuinely wrestling with those questions, this study is designed for you. It doesn’t assume you have already answered them. It works through what Genesis actually says and invites you to think carefully about it."
          },

          {
            "title":"Newer Christians wanting a foundation",
            "body" :"Genesis 1-12 is not just the beginning of the Bible — it is the foundation on which the rest of the Bible is built. If you are relatively new to the Christian faith and want to understand why sin matters, why the world is the way it is, and how God’s plan to rescue it began, this study covers that ground carefully and directly."
          },

          {
            "title":"People discipling others",
            "body" :"If you are walking alongside someone else — as a mentor, a small group leader, or a friend — this study gives you a structured way to work through the foundations together. The eight chapters move from creation to the call of Abram, tracing the shape of God’s story from the very beginning."
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"Individual or Group Study?",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"On your own",
            "body" :"This study works well as a personal study. Work through each chapter at your own pace, read the Bible passages, write your answers, and spend time with the reflection questions at the end. There is no right speed — some chapters may take twenty minutes, others longer if a question stops you in your tracks."
          },

          {
            "title":"In a group",
            "body" :"The study also works well in a small group. You could read the passages and discuss the questions together from scratch. Alternatively — and this is often the most rewarding approach — each person works through the chapter individually first, writes their answers, and then the group meets to discuss what they found. Either way works. The questions are designed to prompt genuine reflection, not just right answers."
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"Group Leaders & Mentors",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"Working with a leader or mentor",
            "body" :"<p>It can make a real difference to have someone guiding you through the study — a group leader, a pastor, or a more experienced Christian who can help you think through your answers and questions.</p><p>At the end of each chapter, the <b>Share</b> button lets you send your written answers directly to your leader or mentor — via WhatsApp, email, or any other app on your phone. This gives them a window into your thinking before you meet, and makes for much richer conversation.</p>"
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"A Note on the Questions",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"Two kinds of questions",
            "body" :"Each chapter has two kinds of questions. The <b>Bible questions</b> are tied to specific passages — asking you to look carefully at what the text actually says. The <b>reflection questions</b> at the end are more personal — asking what the passage means for you specifically, and what you want to carry into your week."
          },

          {
            "title":"The passages are included",
            "body" :"Every Bible question is linked to a specific passage, which is shown in the study so you can read it directly. For longer readings — especially the full chapter passages at the start of each session — you can tap the <b>Read passage</b> button to open the full text. The translation used throughout is the NET Bible."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },

